'''Toyozumi Shrine''' (とよづみじんじゃ) is a {{ill|lt=shrine|Q845945|WD=Q845945|1=Shinto shrine}} in {{ill|lt=Shimizu Ward|Q79385|WD=Q79385|1=Shimizu-ku, Shizuoka}}, {{ill|lt=Shizuoka|Q174691|WD=Q174691|1=Shizuoka (city)}}, {{ill|lt=Shizuoka Prefecture|Q131320|WD=Q131320|1=Shizuoka Prefecture}}. It is a {{ill|UNKNOWN|lt=Shikinaisha|1=Shikinaisha|WD=Q134917286}}, the {{ill|lt=Ninomiya|Q1656379|WD=Q1656379|1=Ichinomiya}} of {{ill|lt=Suruga Province|Q864170|WD=Q864170|1=Suruga Province}}, and its former rank under the {{ill|lt=modern shrine ranking system|Q712534|WD=Q712534|1=Modern system of ranked Shinto shrines}} was {{ill|lt=Gosha|Q134917316|WD=Q134917316|1=Gō-sha}}.

=== Enshrined deity ===
The shrine enshrines the following one deity{{Sfn|明治神社誌料|1912年}}:
* '''{{ill|lt=Konohanasakuya-hime|Q1781862|WD=Q1781862|lt=Konohanasakuya-hime-no-Mikoto|1=Konohanasakuya-hime}}'''

=== History ===
=== Overview ===
According to shrine tradition, it was founded in {{ill|lt=791|Q31078|WD=Q31078|1=791}} ({{ill|lt=Enryaku|Q1373176|WD=Q1373176|1=Enryaku}} 10){{Sfn|豊積神社（平）|2000年}}. It is also said that {{ill|lt=Sakanoue no Tamuramaro|Q941979|WD=Q941979|1=Sakanoue no Tamuramaro}} prayed here for victory during his eastern campaign and, on his return, dedicated kagura in celebration; the Yui Otaiko Festival (prefecturally designated intangible folk cultural property) is said to originate from that kagura<ref name="説明板">Local explanatory signboard.</ref>.

In the ''{{ill|lt=Engishiki|Q1342448|WD=Q1342448|1=Engishiki}}'' {{ill|lt=Jinmyocho|Q11064932|WD=Q11064932|1=Engishiki Jinmyōchō}} compiled in {{ill|lt=927|Q30470|WD=Q30470|1=927}} ({{ill|lt=Encho (era)|Q1327274|WD=Q1327274|lt=Encho|1=Enchō}} 5), "Toyozumi Shrine" is listed under Ihara District ({{ill|lt=Ibara District|Q988501|WD=Q988501|1=Ihara District, Shizuoka}}), {{ill|lt=Suruga Province|Q864170|WD=Q864170|1=Suruga Province}}. This shrine is widely regarded as that listing{{Sfn|豊積神社（平）|2000年}}<ref group="注">For the Engishiki shrine "Toyozumi Shrine," another theory identifies it with Toyoyuke Shrine in Ihara-cho, Shimizu Ward, Shizuoka.</ref>.

In ''{{ill|lt=Suruga no Kuni Fudoki|Q11668491|WD=Q11668491|1=Suruga no Kuni Fudoki}}'', the entry states "Toyozumi Shrine (or Toyoyuke Shrine), place where {{ill|lt=Yamato Takeru|Q461258|WD=Q461258|lt=Yamato Takeru|1=Yamato Takeru}} was worshipped, the Ninomiya of the province," from which it is inferred that this shrine held second rank after {{ill|lt=Fujisan Hongu Sengen Taisha|Q653180|WD=Q653180|1=Fujisan Hongū Sengen Taisha}} (the {{ill|lt=Ichinomiya|Q1656379|WD=Q1656379|1=Ichinomiya}}) in Suruga{{Sfn|中世諸国一宮制|2000年|p=151}}. However, the basis for that statement in the same text is unclear{{Sfn|中世諸国一宮制|2000年|p=151}}.

In the {{ill|lt=Edo period|Q184963|WD=Q184963|1=Edo period}}, its stamped-land allotment was over 16 koku{{Sfn|豊積神社（平）|2000年}}. As seen in documents from {{ill|lt=1589|Q6759|WD=Q6759|1=1589}} ({{ill|lt=Tensho|Q1145058|WD=Q1145058|1=Tenshō (Momoyama period)}} 17), in the early modern period it was also called "Sengen"{{Sfn|豊積神社（平）|2000年}}. A petition from {{ill|lt=1736|Q6989|WD=Q6989|1=1736}} ({{ill|lt=Kyoho|Q1145048|WD=Q1145048|1=Kyōhō}} 21) calls it "Toyozumi Sengen-sha" and claims descent from the Engishiki shrine "Toyozumi Shrine"{{Sfn|豊積神社（平）|2000年}}.

After the {{ill|lt=Meiji Restoration|Q8707|WD=Q8707|1=Meiji Restoration}}, in March {{ill|lt=1873|Q7757|WD=Q7757|1=1873}} ({{ill|lt=Meiji|Q3125096|WD=Q3125096|1=Meiji era}} 6), it was ranked as {{ill|lt=Gosha|Q134917316|WD=Q134917316|1=Gō-sha}} under the modern shrine ranking system{{Sfn|明治神社誌料|1912年}}.

=== Divine rank ===
* Junior Fifth Rank Lower (in ''Suruga no Kuni Shinmeicho''){{Sfn|中世諸国一宮制|2000年|p=151}} - written as "Toyozumi Tenjin."

=== Precincts ===
The main hall is a fully zelkova-built {{ill|lt=nagare-zukuri|Q210684|WD=Q210684|1=Nagare-zukuri}} structure with copper-sheet roofing<ref name="説明板"/>. Ridge tags state it was built in {{ill|lt=1825|Q6997|WD=Q6997|1=1825}} ({{ill|lt=Bunsei|Q1327119|WD=Q1327119|1=Bunsei}} 8), and before that there were constructions in {{ill|lt=1600|Q6720|WD=Q6720|1=1600}} ({{ill|lt=Keicho|Q1328185|WD=Q1328185|1=Keichō}} 5) and rebuilding in {{ill|lt=1732|Q6966|WD=Q6966|1=1732}} ({{ill|lt=Kyoho|Q1145048|WD=Q1145048|1=Kyōhō}} 17)<ref name="説明板"/>. The roof was originally {{ill|lt=cypress bark roofing|Q90373477|WD=Q90373477|1=cypress bark roof}} but was changed to copper sheet in Meiji 22 ({{ill|lt=1889|Q7831|WD=Q7831|1=1889}})<ref name="説明板"/>. After major repairs in Showa 28 ({{ill|lt=1953|Q18585|WD=Q18585|1=1953}}), it reached its current form<ref name="説明板"/>.

Large {{ill|lt=ginkgo|Q43284|WD=Q43284|1=Ginkgo biloba}} and {{ill|lt=camphor|Q158722|WD=Q158722|1=Camphora officinarum}} trees also stand in the grounds.

